<div id="review_4102249907" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4102249907" />
    <a title="Sandie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/845066-sandie"><img alt="Sandie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1632101543p2/845066.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4102249907?book_show_action=true">Sep 26, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sandie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sandie" href="/user/show/845066-sandie">Sandie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780375726156" href="/book/show/89272.John_Brown_Abolitionist">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4102249907" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1864772402819805952">John Brown was responsible for the brutal deaths of pro-slavery men in Bloody Kansas and was executed for his deadly raid on the federal armory in Harper&apos;s Ferry, an action that was intended to trigger the overthrow of slavery in America. His name became a rallying cry for both sides of the Civil War. Was he a holy fool? A madman? A terrorist? A Christ-like martyr ? A devil? or An heroic prophet? Historian and literature professor David S. Reynolds examines the life and legacy of Old Man Brown t</span>
  <span id="freeText1864772402819805952" style="display:none">John Brown was responsible for the brutal deaths of pro-slavery men in Bloody Kansas and was executed for his deadly raid on the federal armory in Harper's Ferry, an action that was intended to trigger the overthrow of slavery in America. His name became a rallying cry for both sides of the Civil War. Was he a holy fool? A madman? A terrorist? A Christ-like martyr ? A devil? or An heroic prophet? Historian and literature professor David S. Reynolds examines the life and legacy of Old Man Brown through the eyes of, not only historians and Brown's contemporaries, but through an examination of American culture and literature.<br /><br />     Reynolds makes convincing arguments for Brown's sanity, his central roles in bringing about the Civil War and ending chattel slavery, and his advancement of Black Americans. <br /><br />     Brown earned the love of ordinary African-Americans and the respect of Black leaders from Frederick Douglass to Malcolm X.  Unlike most his fellow abolitionists (most of whom held racist views), Brown believed unreservedly that African-Americans were his full equals. He also believed in the equality and capacity of people without reguard to race or gender and drew up plans for a addendum to the US Constitution that reflected those beliefs. <br /><br />     As Reynolds' narrative developed, I was struck by the parallels between the growing divide of the North and South in the late 17th century and the rift we are experiencing in the early 21st century. As white northerners became more open to Brown's support for the inclusion of Black people and increasingly came to share his antipathy towards slavery, Southern attitudes about slavery and Black people hardened and Southern opposition often did not let facts stand in their way when they made claims about John Brown and the North. <br /><br />     Reynolds' full and deep work gave me a satisfying answer to my question and left me with a renewed and less (but still) problematical respect for this towering and unique American. I will end (as Reynolds does) with the assessment of Frederick Douglass: "John Brown was right"</span>
  <a data-text-id="1864772402819805952" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


